<dl id="un6006i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un6" href="#un6006">UN6: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un6all.htm#un6006i"> (NLI.4) 6(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> crape weepers, <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="un6006i"><li>Ulysses </li><li><a href="../../ulex/f/lexf.htm#un6006i">2021</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/f/f86.htm#un6006i">2017</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/f/f86.htm#un6006i">1986 (6.603)</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/f/l22f.htm#un6006i">1922</a> </li><li><ms href="#un6006i">MS PL-1</ms> </li><li>JJA 17:226 </li><li><a name="fd6" href="../udra/u6da.htm#fd6">Usage</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/f/fd6.htm#un6006i">Draft: 6.6</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: In a funereal context, crape weepers were trailing hat ornaments (for men in mourning). The undertakers and their staff continued to wear them after they had passed out of fashion, and only the crape armband was generally sported, worn with an ordinary black suit and black tie. </mm> </dd></dl>
